  "market_context": "The market was in a clear downtrend, printing lower highs and lower lows. A prior support level (a swing low) was identified, which later broke and retested as resistance.",
  "key_observation": "A former support level, after being broken downward, acted as resistance on retest—providing a high-probability shorting opportunity in the downtrend.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: The analyst identified a downtrend by observing lower highs and lower lows on the hand-drawn chart (frame f030).",
    "Step 2: A prior support level (swing low) was marked with a horizontal line; the price broke below it, confirming the breakdown (frame f030, f032).",
    "Step 3: The price later retraced to that broken support level, which now acted as resistance—highlighted by a green circle at the retest point (frame f032).",
    "Step 4: On the real USDEUR 4H chart (frame f035), the analyst showed how the broken support zone (around 0.9185–0.9210) became a resistance zone where price rejected upward, confirming the flip.",
    "Step 5: The analyst emphasized that without confirmation signals (e.g., bearish candlestick pattern, volume, momentum), such a trade could fail—illustrating a losing scenario when resistance flipped to support in an uptrend instead."
  ],
  "outcome": null,
  "lessons": "In a downtrend, a broken support level often becomes resistance; retests of that level offer shorting opportunities—but require confluence (e.g., rejection candles, structure break) to avoid false signals.",
